&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work&lt;/strong&gt; is not a state function because it depends on the path taken during a process and not solely on the initial and final states of the system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;State functions, such as pressure, enthalpy, and internal energy, depend only on the system&amp;#39;s current state and are independent of the path used to reach that state.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Work is a process-dependent quantity and is categorized as a path function in thermodynamics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of state functions include temperature, volume, pressure, internal energy, and enthalpy, which are intrinsic properties of the system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike state functions, path functions like work and heat describe energy transfers and require the process to be specified.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;State Functions:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;State functions are properties that depend only on the current state of the system, not on how the system reached that state.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include pressure, temperature, volume, internal energy, Gibbs free energy, and entropy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;State functions are useful for describing equilibrium states and calculating changes in thermodynamic processes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Path Functions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Path functions depend on the specific path or process taken to transition between states.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include work and heat, which are energy transfer quantities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Path functions are often described mathematically using integrals over the process path.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thermodynamic Processes:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thermodynamic processes involve changes in state variables as the system undergoes energy transfer.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common processes include isothermal (constant temperature), adiabatic (no heat exchange), and isobaric (constant pressure).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The work done in a process can vary significantly based on the path followed, even if the initial and final states are the same.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First Law of Thermodynamics:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The first law states that energy cannot be created or destroyed, but it can be transferred or converted between forms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is mathematically expressed as &amp;Delta;U = Q - W, where &amp;Delta;U is the change in internal energy, Q is heat added to the system, and W is work done by the system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Work and heat in this law are path-dependent, while internal energy is a state function.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S-shaped wave&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A sinusoidal wave signal completes one cycle in a characteristic smooth, oscillatory motion resembling an &lt;strong&gt;S-shaped curve&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sinusoidal waves are represented mathematically as &lt;strong&gt;y = A sin(&amp;omega;t + &amp;phi;)&lt;/strong&gt;, where A is the amplitude, &amp;omega; is the angular frequency, and &amp;phi; is the phase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The wave transitions smoothly between its maximum and minimum values, creating a symmetrical &lt;strong&gt;S-shape&lt;/strong&gt; over one complete cycle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sinusoidal waves are fundamental in physics, engineering, and mathematics due to their periodic and harmonic nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Such waves are commonly used in &lt;strong&gt;AC electrical signals&lt;/strong&gt;, sound waves, and other oscillatory systems.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Amplitude:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The maximum displacement of the wave from its mean position.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Represents the strength or intensity of the wave.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequency:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The number of cycles completed per second, measured in Hertz (Hz).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Higher frequency corresponds to faster oscillations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phase:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Defines the offset of the wave relative to a reference point.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Critical for understanding wave interference and synchronization.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Sinusoidal Waves:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in alternating current (AC) electricity supply systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Fundamental to sound wave analysis and signal processing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Critical in studying harmonic motion in physics and engineering.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wave Equation:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A sinusoidal wave can be expressed as y = A sin(2&amp;pi;ft + &amp;phi;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This equation helps model real-world oscillatory phenomena.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;product of force and time&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impulse&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;product of force and the time interval&lt;/strong&gt; over which the force acts. Mathematically, Impulse (J) = Force (F) &amp;times; Time (t).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;Impulse is a vector quantity, as both force and time are involved. It has the same direction as the applied force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;SI unit&lt;/strong&gt; of impulse is the &lt;strong&gt;Newton-second (Ns)&lt;/strong&gt;, which is equivalent to the unit of momentum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;850&quot; data-start=&quot;750&quot;&gt;Impulse is closely related to the concept of &lt;strong&gt;momentum&lt;/strong&gt;. According to the impulse-momentum theorem, impulse is equal to the change in momentum of an object: J = &amp;Delta;p = m &amp;times; &amp;Delta;v.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Impulse is significant in analyzing collisions and impacts. For example, when a baseball bat hits a ball, the force exerted during the short time of contact changes the ball&amp;#39;s momentum, which is described by impulse.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1350&quot; data-start=&quot;1165&quot;&gt;The other options (rate of change of force, change in displacement, product of mass and velocity) are incorrect because they do not represent impulse. &lt;strong&gt;Rate of change of force&lt;/strong&gt; is related to jerk, &lt;strong&gt;change in displacement&lt;/strong&gt; is connected to distance, and &lt;strong&gt;product of mass and velocity&lt;/strong&gt; is momentum, not impulse.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1400&quot; data-start=&quot;1355&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is product of force and time.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impulse and Momentum Theorem:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;The impulse-momentum theorem states that the impulse experienced by an object is equal to the change in its momentum.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;Mathematically, J = &amp;Delta;p = m &amp;times; &amp;Delta;v, where J is impulse, &amp;Delta;p is the change in momentum, m is mass, and &amp;Delta;v is the change in velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2830&quot; data-start=&quot;2700&quot;&gt;This relationship is derived from Newton&amp;rsquo;s second law (F = m &amp;times; a), considering the time interval of the applied force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Impulse:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3000&quot; data-start=&quot;2860&quot;&gt;Impulse is crucial in sports, such as cricket, baseball, and football, where players exert force for a short time to change the momentum of balls.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3150&quot; data-start=&quot;3005&quot;&gt;It is used in designing safety equipment like airbags and helmets to reduce the effect of sudden impacts by increasing the time of collision.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3155&quot;&gt;Impulse is also used in rocket propulsion, where gases are expelled over a short time to generate thrust.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3400&quot; data-start=&quot;3300&quot;&gt;A soccer player kicking a ball applies a force for a short duration, generating an impulse that changes the ball&amp;#39;s speed and direction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3550&quot; data-start=&quot;3405&quot;&gt;In car crashes, the sudden application of force can cause significant damage. Airbags reduce the impact force by increasing the time of collision, thereby reducing the impulse on the passengers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impulse Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;Impulse can be calculated using the formula J = F &amp;times; t, where &lt;strong&gt;F&lt;/strong&gt; is the force applied and &lt;strong&gt;t&lt;/strong&gt; is the time duration of the force.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;If the force is not constant, impulse is calculated as the integral of force over the time interval: J = &amp;int;F dt.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Real-Life Examples:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;During a boxing match, the punch delivered by a boxer generates impulse that affects the opponent&amp;#39;s momentum.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;When a tennis player hits the ball with a racket, the force exerted over a brief time changes the ball&amp;#39;s velocity and direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Insulin&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Insulin&lt;/strong&gt; is a hormone secreted by the &lt;strong&gt;pancreas&lt;/strong&gt;, specifically by the beta cells of the Islets of Langerhans. It plays a critical role in regulating blood sugar levels in the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;The primary function of insulin is to help glucose, obtained from food, enter the cells of the body where it is used for energy. If the secretion of insulin is inadequate, glucose cannot be absorbed by the cells effectively, leading to a condition known as &lt;strong&gt;hyperglycemia&lt;/strong&gt; (high blood sugar levels).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;This inadequate secretion or function of insulin is the primary cause of &lt;strong&gt;Diabetes Mellitus&lt;/strong&gt;, a chronic metabolic disorder. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, insulin is the correct answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;In individuals with diabetes, either the pancreas does not produce enough insulin (Type 1 Diabetes) or the body&amp;rsquo;s cells do not respond effectively to insulin (Type 2 Diabetes).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Proper management of diabetes involves the administration of insulin (for Type 1 Diabetes), medications, lifestyle changes, and dietary adjustments to maintain normal blood sugar levels.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Functions of Insulin:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;Insulin facilitates the &lt;strong&gt;uptake of glucose&lt;/strong&gt; by cells, especially muscle and fat cells, for energy production.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;It helps in the storage of excess glucose in the liver in the form of &lt;strong&gt;glycogen&lt;/strong&gt; for future energy requirements.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;Insulin also plays a role in &lt;strong&gt;fat metabolism&lt;/strong&gt; by promoting the storage of fats in adipose tissues and suppressing the breakdown of fat stores.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Symptoms of Diabetes Mellitus:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequent urination&lt;/strong&gt; (polyuria), excessive thirst (polydipsia), and extreme hunger (polyphagia).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fatigue, blurred vision&lt;/strong&gt;, slow wound healing, and unexplained weight loss are other common symptoms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Importance of Hormones Listed in Options:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Estrogen:&lt;/strong&gt; A female sex hormone responsible for regulating the reproductive system and secondary sexual characteristics in females. It is not involved in blood sugar regulation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Adrenaline:&lt;/strong&gt; A hormone produced by the adrenal glands during stress, which increases heart rate and blood flow, but does not regulate glucose levels.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3729&quot; data-start=&quot;3585&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thyroxine:&lt;/strong&gt; A hormone produced by the thyroid gland that regulates metabolism, but it does not have a direct role in blood sugar control.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Management of Diabetes:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;Type 1 Diabetes is managed by administering &lt;strong&gt;insulin injections&lt;/strong&gt; since the pancreas produces little to no insulin.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;Type 2 Diabetes is managed through a combination of &lt;strong&gt;oral medications, dietary changes, physical activity&lt;/strong&gt;, and sometimes insulin if required.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prevention of Diabetes:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;Adopting a healthy lifestyle, including a &lt;strong&gt;balanced diet, regular exercise&lt;/strong&gt;, and maintaining a healthy weight, can reduce the risk of developing Type 2 Diabetes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;Regular health checkups and monitoring of &lt;strong&gt;blood glucose levels&lt;/strong&gt; are crucial for early detection and management of diabetes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manufacturing and mechanical industries&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tetrachloromethane (carbon tetrachloride)&lt;/strong&gt; is commonly utilized in manufacturing and mechanical industries due to its excellent degreasing properties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This compound is effective in removing grease, oil, and other contaminants from metal surfaces, tools, and machinery.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mechanical industries employ it for cleaning parts during assembly, maintenance, and repair tasks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its non-flammable nature made it a preferred choice in industrial applications before its usage was restricted due to environmental concerns.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Industries like aerospace and automotive heavily relied on Tetrachloromethane for degreasing metal components.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tetrachloromethane (Carbon Tetrachloride):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A chemical compound with the formula CCl&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Historically used as a solvent, cleaning agent, and refrigerant.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its use has significantly declined due to its adverse health effects and contribution to ozone layer depletion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Degreasing Agents:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chemical substances used to remove grease, oil, or dirt from surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include organic solvents, alkaline solutions, and detergents.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are widely applied in industries for cleaning machinery, tools, and metal parts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental Concerns:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Carbon Tetrachloride is classified as a potent ozone-depleting substance under the Montreal Protocol.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its production and use have been phased out in many countries due to its harmful environmental effects.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is also considered a hazardous air pollutant with serious health risks to humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alternative Degreasing Solutions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Eco-friendly alternatives include water-based cleaners and biodegradable solvents.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Industries are increasingly adopting non-toxic and sustainable cleaning agents.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These alternatives help reduce health risks and environmental impact.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Constant Proportions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Law of Constant Proportions&lt;/strong&gt;, also known as the &lt;strong&gt;Law of Definite Proportions&lt;/strong&gt;, was proposed by &lt;strong&gt;Joseph Proust&lt;/strong&gt; in the year &lt;strong&gt;1799&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to this law, a chemical compound always contains the same elements in the same proportion by mass, regardless of its source or the method of preparation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the case of water, it is always composed of hydrogen and oxygen in a fixed &lt;strong&gt;mass ratio of 1:8&lt;/strong&gt;. This means that for every 1 gram of hydrogen, there are 8 grams of oxygen in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This law is universally applicable for pure chemical substances. For example, the ratio of sodium to chlorine in sodium chloride (NaCl) is always constant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given question, the fixed mass ratio of hydrogen and oxygen in water (1:8) is a direct illustration of the &lt;strong&gt;Law of Constant Proportions&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Constant Proportions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Conservation of Energy:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This law states that energy can neither be created nor destroyed; it can only change from one form to another.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It does not apply directly to chemical compositions or fixed mass ratios but rather to energy transformations in physical and chemical processes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Atomic Theory:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Proposed by &lt;strong&gt;John Dalton&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;1808&lt;/strong&gt;, this theory laid the foundation for modern chemistry.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It states that all matter is composed of indivisible atoms, and atoms of a given element are identical in mass and properties.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While the theory aligns with the concept of fixed proportions, it does not specifically address the fixed mass ratio in compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Multiple Proportions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Proposed by &lt;strong&gt;John Dalton&lt;/strong&gt;, this law states that when two elements combine to form more than one compound, the masses of one element that combine with a fixed mass of the other element are in a ratio of small whole numbers.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An example of this is carbon dioxide (CO2) and carbon monoxide (CO), where the ratio of oxygen in CO2 to CO is 2:1 for the same amount of carbon.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This law does not specifically explain the fixed ratio in water but deals with combinations forming multiple compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of the Law of Constant Proportions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Water (H2O):&lt;/strong&gt; Contains hydrogen and oxygen in the mass ratio of 1:8.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbon dioxide (CO2):&lt;/strong&gt; Contains carbon and oxygen in the mass ratio of 3:8.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sodium chloride (NaCl):&lt;/strong&gt; Contains sodium and chlorine in the ratio of 23:35.5 by mass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Application of the Law of Constant Proportions:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This law is applicable only to pure substances. Impure substances or mixtures do not follow this law.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The law is essential in chemical analysis and in determining molecular formulas of compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It forms the basis for stoichiometry, which deals with the quantitative relationships between reactants and products in a chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Limitations of the Law of Constant Proportions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It does not apply to non-stoichiometric compounds, which do not have a fixed chemical composition (e.g., ferrous oxide).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Isotopes of elements may cause variations in mass ratios in some cases.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The law is valid only for homogeneous compounds and fails for heterogeneous mixtures.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Iron is an essential nutrient required for the synthesis of hemoglobin, a protein in red blood cells responsible for oxygen transport in the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Iron deficiency leads to a condition called &lt;strong&gt;iron-deficiency anemia&lt;/strong&gt;, which directly reduces the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The primary symptoms of iron-deficiency anemia include fatigue, weakness, pale skin, and shortness of breath due to insufficient oxygen supply to tissues.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dietary sources of iron include red meat, poultry, fish, legumes, leafy green vegetables, and iron-fortified cereals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Iron absorption is enhanced by vitamin C, whereas substances like calcium and phytates can inhibit its absorption.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hemoglobin:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hemoglobin is a protein in red blood cells that binds to oxygen in the lungs and transports it to tissues throughout the body.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each hemoglobin molecule contains iron, which is critical for its oxygen-binding capacity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron-Deficiency Anemia:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A condition where the body lacks sufficient iron to produce adequate amounts of hemoglobin.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the most common type of anemia globally and can affect people of all ages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of Iron:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Heme iron: Found in animal-based foods like meat and is more easily absorbed by the body.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Non-heme iron: Found in plant-based foods and has lower bioavailability compared to heme iron.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron Absorption:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vitamin C-rich foods like oranges and tomatoes enhance iron absorption.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Calcium, tea, coffee, and whole grains may inhibit iron absorption when consumed together with iron-rich foods.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prevention and Treatment:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Preventing iron deficiency involves consuming a balanced diet rich in iron and vitamin C.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Iron supplements may be prescribed in cases of severe deficiency, under medical supervision.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regulation of hearing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The medulla oblongata is responsible for regulating essential autonomic functions of the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It controls functions such as breathing, heart rate, and blood pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Other functions of the medulla include regulating reflex actions like vomiting, coughing, sneezing, and swallowing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Regulation of hearing is primarily managed by the auditory cortex in the temporal lobe of the brain, not the medulla.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Medulla Oblongata&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The medulla oblongata is a section of the brainstem that connects the brain to the spinal cord.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It plays a crucial role in transmitting signals between the brain and the spinal cord.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Autonomic Nervous System&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The autonomic nervous system controls involuntary physiological functions such as heart rate, digestion, respiratory rate, and pupillary response.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is divided into the sympathetic and parasympathetic systems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Auditory Cortex&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The auditory cortex is located in the temporal lobe and is responsible for processing auditory information.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is crucial for the perception and interpretation of sounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Brainstem&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The brainstem consists of the midbrain, pons, and medulla oblongata.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It controls essential life functions such as breathing, heartbeat, and blood pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Magnification = 0.5&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;formula for magnification (M)&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;M = v/u&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;v&lt;/strong&gt; is the image distance and &lt;strong&gt;u&lt;/strong&gt; is the object distance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the case of a concave lens, the &lt;strong&gt;image is virtual&lt;/strong&gt; and appears on the same side as the object. Thus, the image distance (v) is taken as negative.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, the &lt;strong&gt;focal length (f)&lt;/strong&gt; of the lens is given as &lt;strong&gt;-20 cm&lt;/strong&gt; (negative sign for concave lens).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Image distance (v) is given as &lt;strong&gt;-10 cm&lt;/strong&gt; (negative as the image is virtual).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using the lens formula: &lt;strong&gt;1/f = 1/v - 1/u&lt;/strong&gt;, substitute the values to find u:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1/(-20) = 1/(-10) - 1/u&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Solving this gives &lt;strong&gt;u = -20 cm&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Finally, calculate magnification: &lt;strong&gt;M = v/u = (-10)/(-20) = 0.5&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the magnification produced by the lens is &lt;strong&gt;0.5&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave Lens:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A concave lens is a &lt;strong&gt;diverging lens&lt;/strong&gt; that causes parallel rays of light to spread out.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used in applications such as &lt;strong&gt;correcting myopia (nearsightedness)&lt;/strong&gt;, in optical instruments, and in certain cameras.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The focal length of a concave lens is always &lt;strong&gt;negative&lt;/strong&gt;, and it forms &lt;strong&gt;virtual, upright, and smaller images&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lens Formula:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The lens formula is given as &lt;strong&gt;1/f = 1/v - 1/u&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;f&lt;/strong&gt; is the focal length, &lt;strong&gt;v&lt;/strong&gt; is the image distance, and &lt;strong&gt;u&lt;/strong&gt; is the object distance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This formula applies to both concave and convex lenses, with the respective sign conventions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Magnification:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Magnification is the ratio of the image height to the object height or the ratio of the image distance to the object distance (&lt;strong&gt;M = v/u&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If magnification is &lt;strong&gt;less than 1&lt;/strong&gt;, the image is smaller than the object. If it is &lt;strong&gt;greater than 1&lt;/strong&gt;, the image is larger.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For virtual images formed by a concave lens, magnification is &lt;strong&gt;positive&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Concave Lenses:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eyeglasses:&lt;/strong&gt; Used to correct nearsightedness by diverging light rays before they reach the eye.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Optical Devices:&lt;/strong&gt; Used in telescopes and microscopes to manage the divergence of light rays.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Safety Equipment:&lt;/strong&gt; Used in lasers to spread light evenly and reduce intensity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sign Convention in Lens Formula:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Distances measured in the direction of incoming light are taken as &lt;strong&gt;positive&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Distances measured against the direction of incoming light are taken as &lt;strong&gt;negative&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The focal length of a concave lens is always &lt;strong&gt;negative&lt;/strong&gt;, while that of a convex lens is &lt;strong&gt;positive&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Difference Between Concave and Convex Lenses:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave Lens:&lt;/strong&gt; Diverges light, forms virtual images, and has a negative focal length.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Convex Lens:&lt;/strong&gt; Converges light, forms real or virtual images, and has a positive focal length.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;rolling friction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For a moving solid body, there are &lt;strong&gt;2 principal types&lt;/strong&gt; of friction are following

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rolling friction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sliding friction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On a surface, The force resisting the motion of a rolling body&amp;nbsp;is known as&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Rolling resistance or Rolling friction&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Rolling of a wheel or&amp;nbsp;ball&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;on the ground is an &lt;strong&gt;example &lt;/strong&gt;of Rolling friction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In &lt;strong&gt;Sliding friction&lt;/strong&gt;, there is a restriction on the&amp;nbsp;movement of the body&amp;nbsp;as only one side of the body is in contact with the surface.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;example &lt;/strong&gt;of Sliding friction is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Pushing a box across the table&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Rolling resistance&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;is weaker than &lt;strong&gt;sliding friction&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When 2 surfaces are rubbed against each other, &lt;strong&gt;Sliding friction&lt;/strong&gt; takes place.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When an object rolls on the surface, &lt;strong&gt;Rolling friction&lt;/strong&gt; takes place.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Because of rolling friction, &lt;strong&gt;A basketball rolled on the court will eventually come to a halt&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A&amp;nbsp;broad tire&amp;nbsp;bike will burn extra fuel&lt;/strong&gt; because of the increased Rolling friction.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
